  "description": "High-level overview of Canadian criminal law principles. Covers actus reus, mens rea, defenses, procedure basics, and sentencing concepts. Educational framework only — not legal advice.",
  "topics": [
    {
      "id": "lc_elements_of_offence",
      "title": "Elements of a Criminal Offence (Actus Reus + Mens Rea)",
      "coreDefinition": "Most criminal offences require proof of both a prohibited act (actus reus) and a guilty mind (mens rea). The Crown must prove both elements beyond a reasonable doubt.",
      "frameworkSteps": [
        "Identify the statutory offence under the Criminal Code or other federal statute.",
        "Determine the required actus reus (physical act or omission).",
        "Determine the required mens rea (intent, knowledge, recklessness, or negligence).",
        "Assess whether evidence satisfies both elements beyond a reasonable doubt."
      ],
      "quickExamples": [
        "Theft requires taking property (actus reus) with intent to deprive (mens rea).",
        "Assault requires intentional application of force without consent."
      ],
      "commonMistakes": [
        "Assuming harm alone proves guilt.",
        "Confusing motive with intent."
      ],
